      How to short
   =20
 =20
A problem that we talk about from time to time around here is how to short =
hot startups. The idea is:=09You notice that people are willing to pay a lo=
t of money to invest in hot tech startups.=09You think =E2=80=9Cthese peopl=
e are paying too much, I bet these valuations will come down.=E2=80=9D=09Yo=
u think =E2=80=9CI should borrow some shares of hot tech startups and=C2=A0=
short=C2=A0them; I=E2=80=99ll sell them now, when prices are high, and buy =
them back later, when prices are low.=E2=80=9D=09You realize that you can=
=E2=80=99t do that: Unlike in public markets, it=E2=80=99s=C2=A0essentially=
 impossible to borrow shares of=C2=A0private=C2=A0tech startups, so you can=
=E2=80=99t short them.=09You go to the lab to think up a way to do it.The g=
eneral answer is =E2=80=9Cto bet against a startup bubble, you need to=C2=
=A0create startup shares and sell them.=E2=80=9D The simplest way to do tha=
t is to=C2=A0start a startup, and I have often argued that the single great=
est short seller in the history of private startups is Adam Neumann, who st=
arted=C2=A0WeWork, sold it to Masayoshi Son for $47 billion and has recentl=
y been trying, apparently unsuccessfully,=C2=A0to buy it back for $0.
  [9]
But there are other approaches. We have talked about Destiny Tech100 fund a=
 few times around here. Destiny Tech100 is a publicly traded closed-end fun=
d, with the ticker symbol DXYZ, that owns shares in private tech companies.=
 It trades at a market value, as of yesterday=E2=80=99s close, of about $19=
0 million; its portfolio, as of the end of 2023, was worth about $53 millio=
n. That=C2=A0250+% premium to net asset value=C2=A0was close to the=C2=A0lo=
west=C2=A0it has traded since going public in March; the premium was around=
 2,000% a few weeks ago.DXYZ points to two more ways to short hot tech stoc=
ks. One is forward contracts. As we discussed earlier, a (smallish) portion=
 of DXYZ=E2=80=99s portfolio consists, not of private tech stocks, but of=
=C2=A0forward purchase contracts=C2=A0to buy those stocks. The situation is=
:=09Lots of private startups give their employees stock, but don=E2=80=99t =
allow them to sell it (until the startups eventually go public).=09The empl=
oyees want money now, so they enter a forward contract where (1) they promi=
se to sell their stock to a buyer, at today=E2=80=99s price,=C2=A0when the =
company goes public and they=E2=80=99re able to sell, and (2) the buyer pay=
s them cash now.=09Those forward contracts =E2=80=94=C2=A0future claims on =
startup stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0are financial instruments that can be traded, =
and DXYZ buys some.=09There are some legal and practical risks to these con=
tracts, which are mostly frowned upon by the companies whose stocks are inv=
olved. =E2=80=9CShould the portfolio company object to the existence of the=
 forward contract, it may take any number of steps to discourage or obstruc=
t the transactions,=E2=80=9D warns DXYZ.But for our purposes the lesson is =
obvious: If you want to short hot tech startups, go write forward contracts=
. Create your own shares, via forward. Call up DXYZ, or some other buyer, a=
nd say =E2=80=9Chey I will sell you 10,000=C2=A0shares of Stripe at $25, vi=
a forward.=E2=80=9D You sign the contract, you get your $250,000, you wait.=
 Eventually Stripe goes public and your counterparty comes to you for deliv=
ery, so you go out into the (public) stock market and buy the 10,000 shares=
 you promised. If it goes public at $50 a share and trades up to $100, you =
pay a million dollars for those shares and have a big loss. If it goes publ=
ic at $20 and trades down to $15, you pay $150,000 and have a profit. You j=
ust have a very straightforward short trade.Of course, for your counterpart=
y (DXYZ or whoever), this trade is a little different from their usual forw=
ard contracts. Usually startup-share forwards are written by employees (or =
former employees, early investors, etc.) who=C2=A0own the stock, so they ha=
ve limited credit risk: If a Stripe employee owns 10,000 shares and sells t=
hem forward, and the stock goes up to $100, she doesn=E2=80=99t have to go =
find a million dollars to buy the shares; she already owns them. Her shares=
 were collateral for the forward contract, so her counterparty doesn=E2=80=
=99t have to worry too much about her credit risk. Though=C2=A0traditional =
forwards are=C2=A0not=C2=A0free from credit risk: The company probably does=
n=E2=80=99t allow her to pledge the stock or sell it forward, she might cha=
nge her mind about delivering the stock, and if she does then the counterpa=
rty=E2=80=99s rights to it might be murky. Whereas if you have no relations=
hip with the company and just want to bet against it, and are willing to ca=
sh collateralize your bet, maybe that=E2=80=99s fine.I suppose this is what=
 people in public equity markets call =E2=80=9Cnaked shorting,=E2=80=9D oop=
s. Naked shorting is illegal, when you are trading actual stock for regular=
-way settlement, but I think naked shorts of private stock via forward cont=
ract are probably fine.
  [10]
(Not legal advice!)Second, though,=C2=A0DXYZ itself=C2=A0is just a=C2=A0way=
 to create hot startup shares. We have talked a lot about DXYZ=E2=80=99s la=
rge and volatile premium to its net asset value. In its early days, when it=
s market cap was $875 million, I wrote: =E2=80=9COne way to model this is t=
hat there is $875 million of demand from regular public investors to own sh=
ares in hot private startups, and so far only about $54 million of supply.=
=E2=80=9D DXYZ=C2=A0created=C2=A0the extra supply! It created $875 million =
worth of stock in private companies, while only owning about $54 million wo=
rth of that stock. I wrote:DXYZ should sell stock!=C2=A0So much stock. It s=
hould sell stock to the public at a 1,000% premium to its net asset value o=
r whatever, and then use the money to invest in more stakes in more private=
 companies.=C2=A0And then DXYZ did register to sell more stock. It is selli=
ng stock in a portfolio of private tech stocks, at a high valuation, to rai=
se money to actually go and build that portfolio of private tech stocks. It=
 is selling high=C2=A0today to buy=C2=A0low tomorrow. That=E2=80=99s a shor=
t sale!
