<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Narrower banking</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Barclays Plc is a large global bank, a=
nd it issues credit cards. If you have a Barclays credit card, you can use =
it to buy stuff, in which case Barclays will lend you the money to buy the =
stuff. Some customers pay Barclays back every month; others take years to p=
ay back the money they have borrowed from Barclays to buy stuff. In many wa=
ys, Barclays is well suited to lending them money: As a giant bank, it empl=
oys a lot of people who are good at marketing financial products, people wh=
o are good at making credit decisions, and people who are good at managing =
the payments infrastructure that makes credit cards work. It has branches w=
here people can go to get credit cards, and checking accounts that they can=
 link to automatically pay back their credit cards.</p><p style=3D"margin: =
16px 0;">But Barclays=E2=80=99 ability to issue credit cards is constrained=
 by a simple problem:=C2=A0<em>Where would it get the money?</em>=C2=A0Bloo=
mberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35=
226815.285351/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtM=
DUtMDEvcmVudC10aGUtYmFsYW5jZS1zaGVldC1iYW5rcy1zZWVrLXdheXMtdG8tc2tpcnQtY2Fw=
aXRhbC1ydWxlcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNTAxMjRfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtPWVtYWlsJnV=
0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yNDA1MDEmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWduPW1vbmV5c3=
R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc186191e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=
=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Carmen Arroyo and Katang=
a Johnson report</a> on Barclays=E2=80=99 quest to find a source of money t=
hat it can lend to credit card users:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">For years, Barclays Plc struggled with what to do about its US credi=
t-card business. It was a cash generator, cranking out a steady stream of r=
evenue, and yet it was costly to run because of the way regulators force ba=
nks to set aside capital as a buffer against losses.</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">The British lender came up with a solution in February, by sellin=
g $1.1 billion of card assets to private equity firm Blackstone Inc. The tr=
ansaction, part of an ongoing financing arrangement, allows Barclays to col=
lect fees for servicing the loans, but not have to hold them on its books. =
In return, Blackstone gets to generate high yields for insurance clients.</=
p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In essence, Barclays is renting Blackstone=
=E2=80=99s balance sheet. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The Bar=
clays-Blackstone deal got little attention at the time but may have marked =
a new chapter in the evolution of the lending industry since the global fin=
ancial crisis. As capital rules have gotten tougher, banks have had to exit=
 certain businesses or else cede market share to non-bank rivals. Now, they=
 are partnering with those rivals in ways that benefit both parties =E2=80=
=94 even if it is unclear how regulators might react.</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Soon after Barclays and Blackstone announced their tie-up, KeyCo=
rp and Blackstone unveiled a similar partnership. In interviews, executives=
 at several private-credit providers said they are holding conversations ab=
out more deals, including with some of the largest US banks.</p></blockquot=
e><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have adapted the first two paragraphs abov=
e from <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35226815.28=
5351/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMD=
IvdGhlLWJhbmtzLWFyZS13aGVyZS10aGUtbW9uZXktaXNuLXQ_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMTI0X01PT=
kVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09=
MjQwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB1a135cf6"=
 itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"=
color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px;=
 border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color=
: #ccc;">a column I wrote in November</a>, about JPMorgan =E2=80=9Clooking =
for third-party capital=E2=80=9D to make leveraged loans. I want to keep st=
ressing the oddity of this: The world=E2=80=99s biggest banks, when they po=
nder how to do the=C2=A0<em>very most core business of banking</em>, things=
 like making corporate loans and issuing credit cards, are increasingly con=
strained by the need to=C2=A0<em>find money</em>.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16=
px 0;">The traditional view of banks is that=C2=A0<em>they have lots of mon=
ey:=C2=A0</em>They take deposits from their customers, giving them cheap fu=
nding that they then use to make corporate loans and mortgages and credit c=
ards and everything else.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important=
; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But when the actual bankers at Barclays think about how to fund t=
heir credit cards, they come up with ideas like =E2=80=9Cask Blackstone=C2=
=A0for the money.=E2=80=9D Blackstone has lots of money too, but its money =
comes not from bank depositors =E2=80=94=C2=A0who can withdraw their money =
at any time =E2=80=94=C2=A0but, in this case, from insurance customers, who=
 have longer-term and more predictable liabilities. This makes Blackstone=
=E2=80=99s funding safer: Its customers are not going to ask for their mone=
y back all at once, the way that Barclays=E2=80=99 customers theoretically =
might (and the way that some banks=E2=80=99 customers <a href=3D"https://li=
nk.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35226815.285351/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21=
iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTAvc3RhcnR1cC1iYW5rLWhhZC1hLX=
N0YXJ0dXAtYmFuay1ydW4_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDUwMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lb=
WFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNTAxJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1t=
b25leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB06b28edb" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" item=
scope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decorat=
ion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00000=
0; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">actually have</a>).=
 Everyone knows this, which is why Barclays is subject to strict banking ca=
pital requirements,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; ba=
ckground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0making it expensive for it to do credit-card loans, while Blackst=
one is not,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0making it cheaper for it to provide the money for those loans.</p=
><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, =E2=80=9Ccheaper=E2=80=9D in some sen=
se; Arroyo and Johnson add that =E2=80=9Cbecause non-banks have higher cost=
s of funding, consumers and businesses may see loan rates rise.=E2=80=9D Th=
e traditional view is that non-banks have higher costs of funding than bank=
s: Blackstone=E2=80=99s insurance customers want to earn a juicy return on =
their investment in risky credit-card assets, while Barclays=E2=80=99 depos=
itors are happy to get a return of 0% on their checking-account balances. I=
t=E2=80=99s just that those cheap deposits are not=C2=A0actually<em>=C2=A0<=
/em>so cheap anymore, when you take into account their risk, and the regula=
tion designed to confine that risk. Barclays is in the=C2=A0traditional=C2=
=A0business of lulling depositors into=C2=A0lending it money at 0% so it ca=
n turn around and lend money to credit-card customers at 20%, but that tric=
k no longer works as well as it used to.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">On=
e thing I wonder about is: If you were designing a financial system from sc=
ratch, in 2024, would you come up with=C2=A0<em>banking</em>? That central =
traditional trick of banks =E2=80=94=C2=A0that they fund themselves with sa=
fe short-term demand deposits, and use depositors=E2=80=99 money to invest =
in risky longer-term loans, with all of the run risk and regulatory supervi=
sion and <em>It=E2=80=99s a Wonderful Life</em>-ness that that involves =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0would you recreate that if you were starting over?</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Part of me feels like, if you started a new civilizati=
on and put=C2=A0smart but ahistorical tech people in charge of designing a =
financial system, it would never occur to them to recreate traditional bank=
ing. It is so messy and opaque and imprecise, using a shifting pile of dema=
nd deposits to fund long-term loans. Plenty of people =E2=80=94=C2=A0insura=
nce companies, retirement savers =E2=80=94=C2=A0want to earn a return on th=
eir money and don=E2=80=99t need it anytime soon; <em>their</em>=C2=A0money=
 can be locked up in=C2=A0long-term loans. The money that people keep in th=
e bank just to pay rent and buy sandwiches doesn=E2=80=99t need to be poole=
d and invested in risky loans; it should just sit in the vault.</p><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This idea =E2=80=94=C2=A0that bank deposits should jus=
t sit in the vault (or, realistically, in electronic money at the Federal R=
eserve), while risky loans should be funded by long-term investors who=C2=
=A0<em>intend=C2=A0</em>to take those risks =E2=80=94=C2=A0is sometimes cal=
led =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35226=
815.285351/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMt=
MDQtMjAvYmFua2luZy1nZXRzLWEtYml0LW5hcnJvd2VyP2NtcGlkPUJCRDA1MDEyNF9NT05FWVN=
UVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTI0MD=
UwMSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB12d50692" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">narrow banking</a>.=E2=80=9D It has a long intellectual pedigree, it c=
ame back into vogue after the 2008 financial crisis, and it got attention a=
gain after last spring=E2=80=99s US <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergb=
usiness.com/click/35226815.285351/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGlua=
W9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDMtMTMvc3ZiLWNvdWxkbi10LWlnbm9yZS1pdHMtbG9zc2VzLWJ1=
