ergbusiness.com/click/35226815.285351/aHR0cHM6Ly9ub3RpY2UuY28vYy9zdHJpcGU/6=
07f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB14e6824e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"items=
cope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">$25</a>, via forward.=E2=80=9D Yo=
u sign the contract, you get your $250,000, you wait. Eventually Stripe goe=
s public and your counterparty comes to you for delivery, so you go out int=
o the (public) stock market and buy the 10,000 shares you promised. If it g=
oes public at $50 a share and trades up to $100, you pay a million dollars =
for those shares and have a big loss. If it goes public at $20 and trades d=
own to $15, you pay $150,000 and have a profit. You just have a very straig=
htforward short trade.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Of course, for your =
counterparty (DXYZ or whoever), this trade is a little different from their=
 usual forward contracts. Usually startup-share forwards are written by emp=
loyees (or former employees, early investors, etc.) who=C2=A0<em>own the st=
ock</em>, so they have limited credit risk: If a Stripe employee owns 10,00=
0 shares and sells them forward, and the stock goes up to $100, she doesn=
=E2=80=99t have to go find a million dollars to buy the shares; she already=
 owns them. Her shares were collateral for the forward contract, so her cou=
nterparty doesn=E2=80=99t have to worry too much about her credit risk. Tho=
ugh=C2=A0traditional forwards are=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>free from credit r=
isk: The company probably doesn=E2=80=99t allow her to pledge the stock or =
sell it forward, she might change her mind about delivering the stock, and =
if she does then the counterparty=E2=80=99s rights to it might be murky. Wh=
ereas if you have no relationship with the company and just want to bet aga=
inst it, and are willing to cash collateralize your bet, maybe that=E2=80=
=99s fine.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I suppose this is what people in=
 public equity markets call =E2=80=9Cnaked shorting,=E2=80=9D oops. Naked s=
horting is illegal, when you are trading actual stock for regular-way settl=
ement, but I think naked shorts of private stock via forward contract are p=
robably fine.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-10" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; backgroun=
d-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[10]</span>
</a>(Not legal advice!)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Second, though,=C2=
=A0DXYZ <em>itself=C2=A0</em>is just a=C2=A0<em>way to create hot startup s=
